Featuring a new SoftCoil™delayed gas blow back technology, Walther Arms, Inc. has introduced its latest concealed carry firearm -the CCP.This semi-automatic pistol comes chambered in 9mm and is the ultimate concealed carry weapon.
Weighing only 22 ounces,the CCP’s SoftCoir™ delayed gas blow back system uses gas pressures from the ignited cartridge and feeds them through a small port in the barrel (in front of the chamber) to slow down and delay the rearward motion of the slide. This is accomplished by means of a piston contained inside of a cylinder located under the barrel that opposes the rearward motion of the slide until the gas pressure has declined-after the bullet has left the barrel­ hence allowing the slide to end its rearward motion,opening the breech and ejecting the empty cartridge case. Two other benefits to this system as a result of SoftCoil™technology are that the slide is easily racked and because barrel rise is reduced, the shooter can acquire targets faster. Tests show that the barrel rise is a third less than similar models on the market allowing shooters to be more accurate on follow-up shots.
With an overall length of just 6.5 inches,Walther’s CCP is a sleek solution to concealed carry protection. The new model’s barrel length is 3.54 inches and its width only 1.18 inches making it easily carried in a purse or inside-the-pant holster. The CCP comes in stylish stainless or traditional black and provides all the features that have become signature of Walther’s line of pistols – smooth 5.5 pound trigger pull,interchangeable front sight;adjustable rear sight; and reversible magazine release for left or right handed operation.
This new single-stack semi-automatic has a magazine capacity of 8 rounds. For maximum safety,the CCP comes equipped with a slim manual safety and one internally that acts as a firing pin block. As with all Walther firearms, the CCP has an ergonomic grip with a unique non-slip Hi-Grip™surface. Other key attributes of the gun include an easy access slide stop;loaded chamber indicator for added safety; and front, rear and trigger guard serrations for additional safety and control of its easily manipulated slide.

postcontent:
Offered here is a French Berthier "Mousqueton de Artillerie Modèle 1892 Modifié 1916". Marked Châtellerault. This rifle is dated 1916 and is marked with the "N" on the receiver. Stock, barrel, and trigger guard match. Lock-up is tight and I have personally fired this weapon at 100 yard range and determined it is just as the little carbine is known to be -- very sturdy and accurate! A real pleasure to shoot. The bore is good and I have found no rust or pitting. Rifling is strong. 

Here is a link to comments on my rifle. One estimate of value was 300 Euros ($315).
http://forums.gunboards.com/showthread.php?389846-New-Addition-Berthier-M-16

These guns are not too often found in America. 

Small cut located at bottom of stock is not someone's attempt at making a sporter, but is the site of a French-done wood repair that must have fallen out over the years. This is very common. Also, slot in bottom of stock is not missing sling swivel by accident, but was removed by the French for the Artillery carbine and just never sealed up. Overall, rifle has that nice battle-damaged appearance while still offering a completely strong and serviceable rifle. A piece of history straight from WWI! 

Comes with 4 original 5-shot Mannlicher clips and 48 rounds of black primer (best in my experience) 8mm Lebel (8x50r) ammo. 

$365 or best offer. 

Thanks for your time and shoot me an email!

title: For Sale/Trade:  WWI French Berthier m16 carbine WITH ammo and clips - now for sale
postcontent:
Note: If in West Virginia and wanting to buy, this shooter and piece of WWI history is yours for $310 with ammo and clips. I'll be here until Monday, May 11. l am Based in South Carolina but have property in West Virginia.

Offered here is a French Berthier "Mousqueton de Artillerie Modèle 1892 Modifié 1916". Marked Châtellerault. This rifle is dated 1916 and is marked with the "N" on the receiver. Stock, barrel, and trigger guard match. Lock-up is tight and I have personally fired this weapon at 100 yard range and determined it is just as the little carbine is known to be -- very sturdy and accurate! A real pleasure to shoot. The bore is good and I have found no rust or pitting. Rifling is strong. 

Here is a link to comments on my rifle. One estimate of value was 300 Euros ($315).
http://forums.gunboards.com/showthread.php?389846-New-Addition-Berthier-M-16

These guns are not too often found in America. 

Small cut located at bottom of stock is not someone's attempt at making a sporter, but is the site of a French-done wood repair that must have fallen out over the years. This is very common. Also, slot in bottom of stock is not missing sling swivel by accident, but was removed by the French for the Artillery carbine and just never sealed up. Overall, rifle has that nice battle-damaged appearance while still offering a completely strong and serviceable rifle. A piece of history straight from WWI! 

Comes with 4 original 5-shot Mannlicher clips and 48 rounds of black primer (best in my experience) 8mm Lebel ammo. 

Thanks for your time and shoot me an email!

P.S. Ask for more pictures!

title: For Sale:  Will make your custom molded Kydex holster
location: West Virginia, West Virginia, United States
postcontent:
Do you need a custom holster?  Shoot me a note and we can discuss.  Visit us online: 

https://www.etsy.com/shop/CazGear?ref=hdr_shop_menu

We are located in Virginia and do business online from West Virginia only.

Inside the Waistband (concealed) and Outside the Waistband carry options available.

Common Questions

How much are your holsters? Our holsters normally run $30 for an average size gun with flat basic colors.  Our IWB holsters run $5 more due to a stronger material used.

How much are your mag holsters? Depending on the type, they begin at $24.95.  More complicated holsters with various mag types are available.

Can you make a holster for an FNX .45?  Yes, that is our specialty, making holsters for large, bulky or rare guns is always a challenge.  We aren't happy until you are happy.

What about a Calico M950? Yes, that was one of our most challenging and difficult guns to date.

Do you make holster with custom light/laser attachments? We do not carry "ALL" the custom light/laser attachments and can work with you depending on the model.  In most cases, it is easier if you show up with the gear for us to measure and assess the work needed.

What kind of materials do you have?  We use Kydex, Holstex, and Bolatron in varying sizes from .60 (thin IWB), .80 (medium IWB and OWB), .93 (Thick OWB) to .125. (OWB and complex projects)

What types of holsters do you make?  Inside the waistband (IWB) concealed carry is our specialty but we can make outside the waistband (OWB) as well.  We have designed custom mag carriers for 3 Gun competitions to include mag holsters for a Kriss Vector.

What is your most popular holster? Our most notable is our patent pending "switchblade" made especially for concealed carry.  Very easy to conceal, you can't even feel its there and is designed for faster extraction than traditional style mag holsters.

One of the screws came loose and I lost it, can you replace it? Yes, we offer lifetime warranties on the holsters and will mail you a replacement to keep you going.  We only ask that in certain cases, you pay for shipping costs if required.

Do you make leather holsters? At this time we are not able to make leather holsters but may explore that option at a later date.
